Creating a simple web app that mimics the look and feel of Windows 11 can be done using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Below is a basic example of a single HTML file that includes embedded CSS and JavaScript. This example will create a simple interface with a taskbar, start menu, and a few application icons.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Windows 11 Clone</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
            background-color: #1a1a1a;
            color: white;
        }
        #taskbar {
            position: fixed;
            bottom: 0;
            left: 0;
            right: 0;
            height: 40px;
            background-color: #2d2d2d;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            padding: 0 10px;
        }
        #start-button {
            background-color: #0078d4;
            border: none;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        #start-menu {
            display: none;
            position: absolute;
            bottom: 40px;
            left: 10px;
            width: 200px;
            background-color: #2d2d2d;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            padding: 10px;
        }
        .app-icon {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            padding: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .app-icon:hover {
            background-color: #3a3a3a;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div id="taskbar">
        <button id="start-button">Start</button>
    </div>
    <div id="start-menu">
        <div class="app-icon" onclick="openApp('Notepad')">üìù Notepad</div>
        <div class="app-icon" onclick="openApp('Calculator')">üßÆ Calculator</div>
        <div class="app-icon" onclick="openApp('Settings')">‚öôÔ∏è Settings</div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const startButton = document.getElementById('start-button');
        const startMenu = document.getElementById('start-menu');

        startButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            startMenu.style.display = startMenu.style.display === 'block' ? 'none' : 'block';
        });

        window.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
            if (!startButton.contains(event.target) && !startMenu.contains(event.target)) {
                startMenu.style.display = 'none';
            }
        });

        function openApp(appName) {
            alert(appName + ' opened!');
        }
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML consists of a taskbar with a "Start" button and a hidden start menu that contains a few application icons.
- **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles are embedded in the `<style>` tag and provide basic styling for the taskbar, start button, and start menu.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: The JavaScript code handles the opening and closing of the start menu and simulates opening applications with an alert.

### Usage:
1. Copy the code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `windows11_clone.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser to see the Windows 11 clone interface in action.

Feel free to expand upon this basic structure by adding more features, styles, and applications!
